</p>";}i:10;a:9:{s:5:"title";s:49:"New releases to both versions of ExpressionEngine";s:4:"link";s:89:"http://expressionengine.com/blog/entry/new_releases_to_both_versions_of_expressionengine/";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:11:"Derek Jones";}s:8:"category";s:4:"News";s:8:"comments";s:89:"http://expressionengine.com/blog/entry/new_releases_to_both_versions_of_expressionengine/";s:11:"description";s:2402:"<p>ExpressionEngine has been updated today, both versions: to 1.6.9 and 2.0.2 Public Beta.&nbsp; To view all of the changes, please refer to the change logs for each: <a href="http://expressionengine.com/docs/changelog.html#v169">v1.6.9 Change Log</a> and <a href="http://expressionengine.com/public_beta/docs/changelog.html#v202pb">v2.0.2 Public Beta Change Log</a>.</p>

<p>Active development on ExpressionEngine 1.x has indeed ceased, but support and bug fixes will continue for some time.&nbsp; A particular bug fix relating to the Pages module required a database change, which necessitates a version update rather than only replacing files.</p>

<p>As a result, it is imperative with this release that if you are running any add-ons that utilize the Pages module, or are interacting with the &#8216;site_pages&#8217; array directly via PHP in your templates, you will need to update the add-ons or code per the version update notes: <a href="http://expressionengine.com/docs/installation/version_notes_1.6.9.html">1.6.9 notes</a> and <a href="http://expressionengine.com/public_beta/docs/installation/version_notes_2.0.2.html">2.0.2 notes</a>.&nbsp; Not updating these add-ons or code simultaneous to performing the ExpressionEngine update may result in broken pages. Add-ons that may be affected include Structure, LG Better Meta, and the Nested Menu Plugin.&nbsp; Developers of these add-ons were given pre-release code to have opportunity to update their public releases.&nbsp; Please check for modified versions before updating.</p>

<p>The development team considers this a big milestone for the 2.0 Public Beta, having fixed 130 bugs, restored some extension hooks, and bringing the application closer to our goals for 2.1.</p>

<p>Since we required a database update to 1.x, we did happen to sneak in one feature into 1.6.9 that was suggested to us by Jim at <a href="http://transmodern.net/">Transmodern Media</a>, an enhancement to ExpressionEngine&#8217;s Password Lockout feature.&nbsp; The feature now has additional protection against brute force attacks, an extremely rare event that would often be protected already by use of the Throttling feature, but nonetheless, this feature has been modified to help prevent &#8220;smart&#8221; brute force crackers from trying to play the system, improving the security of accounts on your installation that may be using weak passwords.
</p>";s:4:"guid";s:104:"http://expressionengine.com/blog/entry/new_releases_to_both_versions_of_expressionengine/#When:21:27:53Z";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Thu, 15 Apr 2010 21:27:53 GMT";s:7:"summary";s:2402:"<p>ExpressionEngine has been updated today, both versions: to 1.6.9 and 2.0.2 Public Beta.&nbsp; To view all of the changes, please refer to the change logs for each: <a href="http://expressionengine.com/docs/changelog.html#v169">v1.6.9 Change Log</a> and <a href="http://expressionengine.com/public_beta/docs/changelog.html#v202pb">v2.0.2 Public Beta Change Log</a>.</p>

<p>Active development on ExpressionEngine 1.x has indeed ceased, but support and bug fixes will continue for some time.&nbsp; A particular bug fix relating to the Pages module required a database change, which necessitates a version update rather than only replacing files.</p>

<p>As a result, it is imperative with this release that if you are running any add-ons that utilize the Pages module, or are interacting with the &#8216;site_pages&#8217; array directly via PHP in your templates, you will need to update the add-ons or code per the version update notes: <a href="http://expressionengine.com/docs/installation/version_notes_1.6.9.html">1.6.9 notes</a> and <a href="http://expressionengine.com/public_beta/docs/installation/version_notes_2.0.2.html">2.0.2 notes</a>.&nbsp; Not updating these add-ons or code simultaneous to performing the ExpressionEngine update may result in broken pages. Add-ons that may be affected include Structure, LG Better Meta, and the Nested Menu Plugin.&nbsp; Developers of these add-ons were given pre-release code to have opportunity to update their public releases.&nbsp; Please check for modified versions before updating.</p>

<p>The development team considers this a big milestone for the 2.0 Public Beta, having fixed 130 bugs, restored some extension hooks, and bringing the application closer to our goals for 2.1.</p>

<p>Since we required a database update to 1.x, we did happen to sneak in one feature into 1.6.9 that was suggested to us by Jim at <a href="http://transmodern.net/">Transmodern Media</a>, an enhancement to ExpressionEngine&#8217;s Password Lockout feature.&nbsp; The feature now has additional protection against brute force attacks, an extremely rare event that would often be protected already by use of the Throttling feature, but nonetheless, this feature has been modified to help prevent &#8220;smart&#8221; brute force crackers from trying to play the system, improving the security of accounts on your installation that may be using weak passwords.
</p>";}i:11;a:9:{s:5:"title";s:15:"SXSW 2010 Recap";s:4:"link";s:55:"http://expressionengine.com/blog/entry/sxsw_2010_recap/";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:11:"Derek Jones";}s:8:"category";s:4:"News";s:8:"comments";s:55:"http://expressionengine.com/blog/entry/sxsw_2010_recap/";s:11:"description";s:6800:"<p>SXSW gets bigger every year, with an outward appearance of being this massive overwhelming event where opportunities for focused interaction with individuals seems like a fool&#8217;s hope.&nbsp; And each year we&#8217;ve found new ways to squeeze the most out of it.</p>

<p>This year for much of the weekend we put our schedules into your hands, went where you wanted, and engaged in conversations that were important to you.&nbsp; Between the UserVoice sessions and the meals we hosted, this year seemed to afford more opportunities for in depth conversations with users and developers on how EllisLab can help them to succeed in their businesses.</p>

<p>The diversity was amazing, ranging from people new to ExpressionEngine sharing a table with vets and professional developers, all the way to educators using CodeIgniter in their curriculum.&nbsp; The wide range of interest that SXSW attracts undoubtedly brings together the full spectrum of our users to the same place, and it was a blast.</p>

<p>The <a href="http://www.austinducks.com/">Austin Duck Adventure</a> was a perfect respite, escaping the downtown area out to Lake Austin, where the amphibous bus carrying our 20 guests promptly drove into the water and cruised around in beautiful weather.</p>

<p>Our UserVoice panels packed out the Executive Lounge in the Hilton, and the topics you chose (&#8220;Module Building from the Experts&#8221; and &#8220;CodeIgniter Web Apps with ExpressionEngine&#8221;) certainly kept us on our toes.&nbsp; For those who weren&#8217;t able to attend, there were two big takeaways from these discussions.</p>

<p>The first is that a key ingredient to a successful add-on is the amount of time and thought put into deciding what type of add-on the feature you&#8217;re building is best suited for.&nbsp; Much of that discussion focused on the new add-on type, Accessories, as they give both novices and expert developers alike nearly unlimited power to add persistent information to the ExpressionEngine control panel without any hacks or worrying with Extensions.</p>

<p>The second was a discussion about how a CodeIgniter application can benefit from running alongside or from within ExpressionEngine.&nbsp; Some applications are suited to run outside of the ExpressionEngine instance (a request heavy application that doesn&#8217;t need all of ExpressionEngine&#8217;s abilities for instance) and others are well suited to make extremely minor additions to allow them to run as fully built ExpressionEngine add-ons.&nbsp; Attendees were spitballing integration ideas, culminating in a long pause followed by a &#8220;wow, you&#8217;re blowing my mind&#8221; from one guest.</p>

<p>The highlight for us personally had to be Monday&#8217;s &#8220;ExpressionEngine 2.0: Total Domination&#8221; panel, with <a href="http://www.happycog.com/">Happy Cog</a> speakers Ryan Irelan, Jenn Lukas, Brian Warren, and Mark Huot, moderated by Kenny Meyers.&nbsp; This crew did such a fabulous job (neither authored nor even sponsored by EllisLab, incidentally) that SXSW staff were commenting about how it was the best panel they had seen all weekend.&nbsp; <a href="http://eeinsider.com/blog/sxsw-expressionengine-panel-slides/">The slides</a> will give you a summary of the content, but they can&#8217;t capture just how well each speaker brought their topics to life.</p>

<p>Kenny introduced the audience to ExpressionEngine, with user quotes from Obama and Zeus.&nbsp; He then introduced Ryan Irelan who showed how easy it is to use ExpressionEngine to build sites from any source of content, showcasing a racing client who used Twitter, Twitpics, and Twitvids to publish and share their media.&nbsp; ExpressionEngine was employed in a way that used entries to control the featured content of the site, aggregating this rich content from external services that the race team used through the day of a race.</p>

<p>Jenn Lukas&#8217;s philosophy is that every site is different, but they&#8217;re also all a little bit the same.&nbsp; She really went the extra mile and launched a new site: <a href="http://starterfiles.com/">ExpressionEngine Starter Files</a>, a robust set of files meant to drop in place in an ExpressionEngine 2.0 installation as a starting point for the creation of any ExpressionEngine powered site.</p>

<p>Brian Warren delved into the power of Accessories (the ExpressionEngine buzz word this year, it seems), showing how to harness their power to benefit your sites and your clients.&nbsp; Two featured Accessories were Derek Hogue&#8217;s beautiful <a href="http://devot-ee.com/add-ons/accessories/cp-analytics/">Google Analytics accessory</a> and Newism&#8217;s <a href="http://github.com/newism/nsm.addon_updater.ee_addon">Addon Updater</a>.</p>

<p>Veteran developer Mark Huot talked about the Channel API: ExpressionEngine 2.0&#8217;s methods for interacting with your entries and Channel related metadata.&nbsp; Especially considering that this API is not yet fully documented for third party developers, Mark did a fantastic job of showcasing how much time and coding energy the new APIs can save.&nbsp; It was great to see some of these fundamental changes made in ExpressionEngine 2.0&#8217;s underlying architecture already benefitting developers, even while still in public beta.</p>

<p>They ended with a Q&amp;A session, and we were practically blushing when someone who was completely new to ExpressionEngine asked on mic if the community was any good and the audience spontaneously erupted in a rowdy affirmative.&nbsp; You guys rock.</p>

<p>That night, Robert Earhart of Whoooz! Media hosted the EECI preParty at The Library, generously providing pizza, drinks, and a space (complete with pool tables) for the community to hang out and chat about the <a href="http://eeci2010.com/">upcoming conference</a> in San Francisco.&nbsp; He also gave away three tickets to the May event, and we announced the random drawing winner of an EllisLab sponsored full conference pass: <a href="http://expressionengine.com/forums/member/35906/">Jesse Schutt</a>.&nbsp; Congratulations, Jesse!</p>

<p>If the audience gathered at the EECI preParty was any indication, this event is one that you do <em>not</em> want to miss.&nbsp; The opportunities for learning, sharing, and networking with fellow ExpressionEngine and CodeIgniter professionals is unparalleled.</p>

<p>SXSW 2010 was a wonderful event and this post only touches the tip of the iceberg.&nbsp; This year it really was all about you, and we could easily fill a book with the details of the conversations and connections made.&nbsp; A big thanks from all of us to those that were able to join us; we can&#8217;t wait until May to join up with you again and to meet those that couldn&#8217;t make it to SXSW!
</p>";s:4:"guid";s:70:"http://expressionengine.com/blog/entry/sxsw_2010_recap/#When:22:57:59Z";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Thu, 01 Apr 2010 22:57:59 GMT";s:7:"summary";s:6800:"<p>SXSW gets bigger every year, with an outward appearance of being this massive overwhelming event where opportunities for focused interaction with individuals seems like a fool&#8217;s hope.&nbsp; And each year we&#8217;ve found new ways to squeeze the most out of it.</p>

<p>This year for much of the weekend we put our schedules into your hands, went where you wanted, and engaged in conversations that were important to you.&nbsp; Between the UserVoice sessions and the meals we hosted, this year seemed to afford more opportunities for in depth conversations with users and developers on how EllisLab can help them to succeed in their businesses.</p>

<p>The diversity was amazing, ranging from people new to ExpressionEngine sharing a table with vets and professional developers, all the way to educators using CodeIgniter in their curriculum.&nbsp; The wide range of interest that SXSW attracts undoubtedly brings together the full spectrum of our users to the same place, and it was a blast.</p>

